content.problemStatement:
Okay, so we've set up our EJS template engine. Now let's talk about making our web pages more interesting by rendering dynamic content! "Dynamic content" simply means content that changes based on different factors, like user input or data from our server.

Think of it like this: instead of just showing the same static HTML page every time, we want to insert data into our templates. This data can come from anywhere – maybe a variable in our Node.js code, or a calculation we perform on the server.

EJS makes this easy with special tags. The most common tag we'll use is ``. Anything you put inside these tags will be evaluated as JavaScript, and the result will be inserted into the HTML.

Let's say we have a variable in our Node.js code called `name`:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const port = 3000;

app.set('view engine', 'ejs'); // Remember this from the last lesson?

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  const name = "John Doe"; // Our dynamic data!
  res.render('index', { userName: name }); // Passing data to the view
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`Server listening at http://localhost:${port}`);
});
```

In this code, we're defining a variable `name` with the value "John Doe". Now, we want to display this name in our `index.ejs` template. Notice how we pass the `name` variable to the `res.render` function inside an object `{ userName: name }`. This makes the `name` variable accessible inside our EJS template using the key `userName`.

Here's how our `index.ejs` file might look:

```html



    Dynamic Content Example


    Hello, ! 
    Welcome to our website.


```

See the ``? This is where the magic happens. When Express renders the template, it will replace this tag with the value of the `userName` variable we passed from our Node.js code (which is "John Doe").

So, when a user visits the homepage, they'll see:

```html
Hello, John Doe!
Welcome to our website.
```

That's dynamic content in action! We're inserting data from our server into the HTML before it's sent to the browser.

We can also use other JavaScript expressions inside the `` tags. For example, we can perform calculations or access properties of objects.

For instance, if we send an array to our template:

```javascript
app.get('/items', (req, res) => {
  const items = ["Item 1", "Item 2", "Item 3"];
  res.render('items', { items: items });
});
```

Then, in `items.ejs`, we can access individual items:

```html



    Items


    Here are the items:







```

This would render a list of the items.

This is just a basic example, but it shows the power of rendering dynamic content. You can use this technique to display all sorts of information on your web pages, making them much more interactive and engaging. In the next lesson, we'll dive deeper into passing different types of data to our views.

